Samsung’s Galaxy Note 20 and Note 20 Ultra smartphones are now available in South Africa, offering high-end performance and cutting-edge technology. These devices offer powerful features such as 8K camera capabilities, S-Pen styluses, bezel-less displays, and 5G connectivity. The Galaxy Note 20 smartphones also include performance optimisation for mobile gaming, wireless sync with desktop and laptop PCs, and improved DeX features for remotely connected to compatible devices. The prepaid prices of the Samsung Galaxy Note 20 and Note 20 Ultra smartphones are as follows: If you want to purchase one of these new smartphones but don’t have more than R20,000 on hand, however, you can take out a contract with one of South Africa’s mobile networks. Whether you purchase a new Galaxy Note 20 or Note 20 Ultra smartphone on contract or prepaid, you will be able to benefit from Samsung’s launch promotion. Samsung offers South African Galaxy Note 20 and Note 20 Ultra buyers a launch gift if they purchase one of the new devices within a specific period. The company states that South Africans who buy a new Galaxy Note 20 smartphone will receive a free UV smartphone sterilizer, as well as a significant discount on Samsung Care+. Samsung Care+ provides accidental damage protection for 24 months and will be available to qualifying buyers for only R499 once-off. This limited-time offer is exclusive to the Samsung Galaxy Note 20 and Note 20 Ultra and must be redeemed before 7 October 2020. South Africans who purchase a Samsung Galaxy Note 20 smartphone through a mobile operator will need to download the Samsung Members app to redeem this gift. Through this app, they must submit proof of purchase and they will receive a tracking number. Once their submission has been validated, they will be able to claim their gift from the Samsung online store. Vodacom, MTN, Telkom, and Cell C each offer a range of contract options for the Samsung Galaxy Note 20 and Note 20 Ultra. We have compared a number of the best contract deals for the LTE and 5G variants of the new smartphones below. <img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-362790" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Samsung-Galaxy-Note-20-1-640x430.jpg" alt="Samsung Galaxy Note 20 1" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Samsung-Galaxy-Note-20-1.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Samsung-Galaxy-Note-20-1-595x400.jpg 595w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Samsung-Galaxy-Note-20-1-300x202.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> <img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-365580" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-note-20-640x430.jpg" alt="Galaxy note 20" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-note-20.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-note-20-595x400.jpg 595w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-note-20-300x202.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> <img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-363640" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-Note-20-Ultra-5G-640x430.jpg" alt="Galaxy Note 20 Ultra 5G" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-Note-20-Ultra-5G.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-Note-20-Ultra-5G-595x400.jpg 595w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Galaxy-Note-20-Ultra-5G-300x202.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> <img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-362796" src="https://mybroadband